description:
Although it's a cheap cliche to reference Tom Waits if discussing dive bars and booze, when Waits sings about the time that he "drank with all the Chinamen," I can't help but think he's referring to the Li Po lounge.

This small, antique, and unpretentious Chinatown dive lies behind a set of double doors cut out of a cave wall. Inside, the ceiling and walls are painted with historical murals and alphabetical motifs. Traditional Chinese lanterns hang and glow overhead, including one so immense in size that you could hide inside it like a cocoon. A buddha statue smiles mysteriously in an altar behind the bar. The room snakes around the corner, revealing dingy leather booths. And a staircase curls down to the basement, where dank bathrooms -- and, on some nights, a concrete storage room where punk bands blare away in amateur abandon -- wait with dilapidated patience for your inevitable visit.

But the best thing about Li Po, in my opinion, is that it's named after a poet. At a time when so many new lounges are opening with meaningless, glamour-sucking titles like "Glow" or "Suave" or "Swank,"  this old cocktail cave's honoring of a man who sought wisdom over wealth makes me happy. Besides, Li Po was also an infamous lover of alcohol -- a perfect role model for any aspiring bar owner.

And so I guess I'll complete this review with the words of Li Po himself:

Among flowers with a pot of liquor;
I pour alone but with no friend at hand;
So I lift the cup to invite the shining moon;
Along with my shadow, a fellowship of three.
